<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-08-02T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-08-02T02:00:00-05:00" n="536" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d536">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01/8–249: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Taipei</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Macdonald</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Taipei</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-08-02T16:00:00+09:00">August 2,
                                    1949—4 p. m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received August 5—1:23 p. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>346. Information mytel 344, repeated to Canton 153 August 2, confirmed
                            officially. Informant said however this organization should not be
                            called headquarters but Gimo’s private secretariat. It is also referred
                            to as Tsungtsai’s office (office of the Director General of the
                            Kuomintang).</p>
                        <p>Sent Department 346, repeated Canton 155.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Macdonald</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>